		<a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=3723'>Putz</a></font><BR><BR>Response:<BR><font face='verdana, arial' size='2' color='ee3333'></font><BR><BR> <font class="afont">( was not much help )</font></TD></TR><TR><TD align='right' valign='top'><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top'><font class="bfont">Well I agree with everyone else, it is a well written article.  What I disagree with is the whole thing about 5+ companions.  I have *never* played with more than four companions, because LOOK at all the shadow cards out there that totally SCREW over 5+ companion fellowships; just think of what Enquea can do to a 6 companion fellowship if Not Easily Destroyed is on the table.  He can wax Aragorn and then his job is done.  I know the whole thing is about getting rid of companions, either letting them die or killing them as the shadow, but this is a blantent WASTE of Aragorn.  The best deck I have built revolves around just Frodo and Sam, and the hobbit supporters, and many promises to pump us up.  My point is, even though you want to just blow companions, that adds twilight to play them, it adds more twiligh to the pool when you move, and they take up cards in your deck where pumps, possessions, and ELENDIL&#39;S VALOR should be!  Defender +1 is the best option for fellowships because let&#39;s face it... Men have the most winning strategy right now.  <br>
If I can HEAL the wounds, I don&#39;t need to blow the lives of companions.  And if I can choke the pool, then there are few losers to come at me :)  <font size=1>(+2 tp)</font><BR>
		<a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9485'>Elven Sage</a></font><BR><BR>Response:<BR><font face='verdana, arial' size='2' color='ee3333'></font><BR><BR> <font class="afont">( was very helpful )</font></TD></TR><TR><TD align='right' valign='top'><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top'><font class="bfont">I did love the abuse of a famous soliloquy but have to say you don&#39;t have to use a fellowship of more than 4 companions, it can be very useful to have an uberfellowship but often the small choke based fellowship decks can do very well and don&#39;t fall prey to the nastiness of certain uruks and nazgul.  <br>
<br>
On the other hand I&#39;ve played a deck with around 7 companions in total and never had more than 4 or 5 out at a time because I chose when to kill a surplus companion in order to play a more useful person to my fellowship.  Dealing with the death of a companion in this way can be key to winning a game, be it soaking up wounds or taking the big one vs the balrog, troll or lurtz.  In fact there are times when certain companions are more key for my deck than others and I&#39;ll chump block with Sam, SoH once his useful burden removal is done so that Aragorn or Boromir don&#39;t just survive but take one less wound.  <br>
<br>
Hey if they have that many wounds on them and aren&#39;t that important to you they may as well be allowed to die so you have less wounds to decide on healing later, that may be a twisted form of logic but it works for me.  Plus, and I&#39;m not sure you mentioned it, allowing a companion to die can throw your opponent.  It&#39;s very useful if they start to underestimate you because they&#39;ve managed to kill one of your companions...congrats on another good article.  <font size=1>(+4 tp, Double-Edged Sword)</font><BR>
